As for the SC calculations of three-electrode systems using GCD curves, the following formula is applied:9SC=I∫T1T2ΔsmΔV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\text{SC}} = \frac{{{\text{I}}\mathop \smallint \nolimits_{T1}^{T2} \Delta s}}{m\Delta V} $$\end{document}where SC (F g−1), I(A), ΔS, m (g), and ΔV (V) are referred to specific capacitance, real current discharge, integrated area of discharge curves, active mass of the single working electrode, and potential window. The equation for the asymmetric cell operates in a pretty similar fashion, but with a minor change in that the numerator is multiped by two. For 'm' average active mass of both electrodes is considered (equal mass).
